Data Mining - Car Insurance Customer Cold Call (Customer Segmentation)

Jason Jia

2019-07-31

Solutions

In this script, I examined the historical data from 4,000 previous calls and mailings for the line of credit offer. Using this historical data and any supplemental data, create a propensity model, evaluate it, and identify by uniqueID the top 100 households to contact from the prospective customer list. I also identified learn more about the customer profile for historical and top prospective customers.

### KNN ###

                data = na.omit(treatedTrain), #data input

                preProcess = c("center","scale"), tuneLength = 10) #normalization

#------------------------------------------------------------------------
### Classification Tree
# use rpart() to run a classification tree.
# define rpart.control() in rpart() to determine the depth of the tree.
class.tree <- rpart(Y_AcceptedOffer ~., 
                    data = treatedTrain,  method = "class")
#plot a tree
prp(class.tree, type = 1, extra = 1, split.font = 1)  

deeper.tree <- rpart(Y_AcceptedOffer ~., 
                     data = treatedTrain,  method = "class", cp = 0, minsplit = 50)
prp(deeper.tree, type = 1, extra = 1, under = TRUE, split.font = 1, varlen = -10, 
    box.col=ifelse(deeper.tree$frame$var == "<leaf>", 'gray', 'white'))  

# set argument type = "class" in predict() to generate predicted class membership.
default.ct.point.pred.train <- predict(deeper.tree,treatedTrain,type = "class")
default.ct.point.pred.test <- predict(deeper.tree,treatedTest,type = "class")

#confusion matrix
cm_ct_train <- confusionMatrix(default.ct.point.pred.train, 
                               as.factor(treatedTrain$Y_AcceptedOffer))
cm_ct_test <- confusionMatrix(default.ct.point.pred.test, 
                              as.factor(treatedTest$Y_AcceptedOffer))


#accuracy
sum(diag(cm_ct_train$table)) / sum(cm_ct_train$table) #0.80375
## [1] 0.80375
sum(diag(cm_ct_test$table)) / sum(cm_ct_test$table)  #0.70625
## [1] 0.70625
#Will do the same for the pruned tree
printcp(deeper.tree)

### Random Forest 

rf <- randomForest(as.factor(Y_AcceptedOffer) ~ .,
                   data = na.omit(treatedTrain),
                   ntree = 500, 
                   mtry = 4,
                   nodesize = 5,
                   importance = TRUE)  


varImpPlot(rf, type = 1)

## NOW TO GET PROSPECTIVE CUSTOMER RESULTS
# 1. Load Raw Data
prospects <- read.csv("ProspectiveCustomers.csv")

# 2. Join with external data
join <- left_join(prospects, newDataSource, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining factors with different levels,
## coercing to character vector
join2 <- left_join(join, newDataSource2, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
prospData <- left_join(join2, newDataSource3, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
# 3. Apply a treatment plan
treatedProsp <- prepare(plan, prospData)

# 4. Make predictions
prospectPreds <- predict(fit_lm_backward, treatedProsp, type = "response")

# 5. Join probabilities back to ID
prospectsResults <- data.frame("HHuniqueID" = prospects$HHuniqueID, "Probability" = prospectPreds)

# 6. Identify the top 100 "success" class probabilities from prospectsResults
ordered <- prospectsResults[order(prospectsResults$Probability, decreasing = "T"),]

top <- ordered[1:100,]

#### ANALYZING PROSPECTIVE CUSTOMERS
top1 <- left_join(top, newDataSource, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining factors with different levels,
## coercing to character vector
top2 <- left_join(top1, newDataSource2, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
finaltop <- left_join(top2, newDataSource3, by = c('HHuniqueID'))
## Warning: Column `HHuniqueID` joining character vector and factor, coercing
## into character vector
#Age and gender distribution
ggplot(data = finaltop) + 
  geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = Age, fill = headOfhouseholdGender),  binwidth = 5,)

#Gender
ggplot(data = finaltop) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = headOfhouseholdGender))

finaltop$HHInsurance <- as.factor(finaltop$HHInsurance)
finaltop$CarLoan <- as.factor(finaltop$CarLoan)

ggplot(data = finaltop) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = headOfhouseholdGender, fill = HHInsurance))

#Car Brand
ggplot(data = finaltop) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = carMake,)) +coord_flip()

#CarLoan, Insurance
ggplot(data = finaltop)+

#Digital habits ~ Age
ggplot(data = finaltop) +
